---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Morning Briefing - 07/13/26: Power Grab TX">
  <div class="post-page">
    <div class="post-content">
      <h1>⭐ Morning Briefing — Texas &amp; DFW AI Data Centers, Grid, Land Use</h1>
      <p class="briefing-subtitle">(Latest updates through July 13, 2026)</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>⚡ 1. ERCOT &amp; Grid Signals</h2>
      <p class="section-tagline">Load Growth • Queue Pressure • Transmission Stress</p>
      <ul>
        <li>ERCOT's large‑load queue remains historically high, with AI‑center requests dominating new submissions.</li>
        <li>The readiness‑test filter continues to remove speculative projects; watch for any approvals today.</li>
        <li>Transmission planners highlight North Texas congestion zones — Denton, Wise, western Tarrant — as priority stress points.</li>
        <li>No overnight emergency notices, but summer reserve margins remain thin.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Today's Signal:</strong> Any ERCOT notice mentioning large‑load studies, queue reform, or transmission constraints deserves immediate attention.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>🏗️ 2. Data Center Construction &amp; Corporate Activity</h2>
      <p class="section-tagline">New Builds • Land Acquisition • On‑Site Power</p>
      <ul>
        <li>DFW remains one of Texas's most active build zones, with quiet land buys near substations and transmission corridors.</li>
        <li>Operators continue shifting toward on‑site generation (gas + battery) to reduce ERCOT dependence.</li>
        <li>Watch for filings from Meta, AWS, Google Energy LLC, and private‑equity infrastructure groups — these often appear first as interconnection requests or air‑permit filings.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Today's Signal:</strong> Any corporate language referencing AI‑optimized compute, behind‑the‑meter power, or hybrid generation indicates a high‑load campus.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>🌿 3. Environmental &amp; Air‑Permit Activity (TCEQ)</h2>
      <p class="section-tagline">Gas Plants • Emissions • Community Pushback</p>
      <ul>
        <li>TCEQ's docket shows steady applications for gas‑fired generation tied to data centers across North and West Texas.</li>
        <li>Environmental groups continue highlighting cumulative emissions concerns for multi‑plant clusters.</li>
        <li>Collin, Ellis, and Johnson Counties show early community resistance around air quality and groundwater.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Today's Signal:</strong> Any new TCEQ draft permit or public‑comment notice for a gas plant near DFW is a high‑priority alert.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>🏛️ 4. Land‑Use &amp; Zoning Developments</h2>
      <p class="section-tagline">DFW Counties • Rural Tension • Industrial Masking</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Developers are filing "warehouse/industrial" zoning requests that often mask data‑center intent.</li>
        <li>Rural counties with minimal zoning (Parker, Hood, Wise) continue attracting speculative land purchases near transmission corridors.</li>
        <li>Urban operators are pivoting toward brownfield redevelopment to avoid rural opposition.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Today's Signal:</strong> Check county commissioner agendas for large‑parcel industrial proposals near substations — these are often early data‑center footprints.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>🔌 5. Power‑First Strategies &amp; On‑Site Generation</h2>
      <p class="section-tagline">Gas + Battery • Self‑Supply • Grid Relief</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Texas continues to see proposals for dedicated gas plants serving AI campuses directly.</li>
        <li>Behind‑the‑meter generation reduces ERCOT load but increases local environmental and land‑use impacts.</li>
        <li>Operators are exploring gas + battery hybrids to meet ride‑through requirements.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Today's Signal:</strong> Any filing mentioning on‑site generation, hybrid gas, or self‑supply is strategically important.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>📍 6. Today's Watch List</h2>
      <p class="section-tagline">Actionable Signals for Monday</p>

      <h3>ERCOT</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Large‑load queue updates</li>
        <li>Readiness‑test approvals</li>
        <li>Any notice on transmission constraints or large‑load study changes</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>PUC</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Dockets involving large‑load integration</li>
        <li>Rulemaking discussions affecting interconnection timelines</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>TCEQ</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>New air‑permit filings for gas‑fired generation</li>
        <li>Draft permits or public‑comment notices near DFW counties</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>County Zoning (DFW + Surrounding Counties)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Industrial/warehouse zoning proposals</li>
        <li>Large‑parcel filings near substations or transmission corridors</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Corporate Filings</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Interconnection requests from hyperscale operators</li>
        <li>Land‑purchase disclosures tied to AI or on‑site generation</li>
        <li>Any mention of behind‑the‑meter or hybrid gas‑plus‑battery power</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="post-related">
        <h3>Related Pages</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="/trackers">AI Data Center Tracker</a> — The full running, dated record of Texas AI data center developments.</li>
          <li><a href="/news">Latest News</a> — Updates on Texas energy, AI expansion, and infrastructure changes.</li>
          <li><a href="/stay-informed">Stay Informed</a> — Get alerts and updates about developments affecting Texas communities.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
<style>
  /* ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       MOVE TO → src/pages/briefings/[slug].astro
       Briefing-specific styles: subtitle, section dividers, and
       the "Signal" callout used to close out each section.
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ */

  .briefing-subtitle {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    text-align: center;
    color: #666;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  .post-content h1 {
    text-align: center;
  }

  .section-divider {
    border: none;
    border-top: 1px solid #e8c9b0;
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
  }

  .section-tagline {
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    color: #b03a1a;
    margin-top: -0.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.8rem;
  }

  .signal {
    background: #fff8f4;
    border-left: 4px solid #e05c2a;
    padding: 0.8rem 1rem;
    border-radius: 4px;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    color: #3a2010;
  }
</style>
